<font color="#FF0000">LESSONS?</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 16  9:10:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lessons learned from 'Nam -<br><br>
Sorry to say, hardly any.  Here's what I learned:<br><br>
1).  America, while well-intentioned most of the time, is capable of great evil.  It is no different from any other human organization; it can be well-led or mis-led, and lots of folks have their own ax to grind.<br><br>
2).  Despite that, many of the much-reviled &quot;politicians&quot; were as idealistic as I was when I joined the Crotch in Jan of '68 to &quot;save the South Vietnamese&quot;.  They really wanted to help those people.  However, they forgot to ask if &quot;those people&quot; wanted our help.<br><br>
3).  It's damn easy to point fingers, a hell of a lot harder to take responsibility.<br><br>
4).  Most folks (vet or not) tried to do their best.<br><br>
5).  History is full of important lessons, which we ignore because we don't like to look back.<br><br>
6).  Next time we fight a war, let's and make goddamn good and sure that a).  there's no other way  b).  it is really vitally important for our country or for people who want and need our help.<br><br>
Hey Cook - 3rd battalion, 1st Marines 25 June 1968 to 19 July 1969.  I was a 2531.  Spent some time in some of the areas you were talking about.
